  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti chapter 8, the rules on physical assault (starting at verse 279) specify penalties that distinguish between castes and the nature of the offense.**[^1]\n\nA foundational rule states that if a person of lower *varṇa* (e.g., non-Brāhmaṇa) injures a superior (e.g., a Brāhmaṇa), the offending limb shall be cut off.[^2]\n\nThe precise case matching \"points a weapon (without using it)\" appears in the very next verse: \"He who **raises his hand or a stick** deserves to have **his hand cut off**\" (the stick qualifies as a basic weapon, and \"raises\" implies threatening/pointing without necessarily striking).[^3]\n\nThis rule follows immediately after penalties for insults (e.g., verbal abuse) and precedes those for actual striking, wounding, or bone-breaking, confirming it addresses threats/gestures short of contact. Penalties escalate with injury level and *varṇa* disparity (e.g., a Shūdra assaulting a Brāhmaṇa is far harsher than equals), but no verse uses \"points a weapon\" verbatim—though a stick/weapon raised fits this threat context precisely.[^4]\n\n**Manusmṛti ch.8 does not cover every hypothetical (e.g., equals or Brāhmaṇa offender), but this is the direct match for a non-Brāhmaṇa threatening a Brāhmaṇa.**\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, ch.8, [full chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti* 8.279, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-526528).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti* 8.280, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-c0dabc).\n\n[^4]: *Manusmṛti* 8.278–284 (assault sequence), [passage](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-526528).",
